Should have a surprise ready for you guys in 24 hours. In the meantime:
>>46820967
https://archiveofourown.org/works/38105683
Review for
>And the mythic bleats were true
by Neton
It's a cute little period piece, albeit with some minor issues.
>I hope mom is okay with me not attending that Ishtar thing this year
'Ishtar thing' seems somewhat anachronistic, why not describe it as the fertility festival or something? A little more research could have been done here.
Your sentences tend to go on forever while having breaks scattered around haphazardly.
>They looked at me, doubtful, while they looked up and down at me, my garments and my package to give, and they accepted me.
A good general rule is to keep your sentences to a limit of two commas or less unless absolutely necessary, and even reduce them where you can. If you find your self using three or more commas outside of a list, you should probably consider breaking up the sentence with a semicolon, colon or full stop instead.
It's a pretty solid establishment of a setting, and I'd love to see you or someone else cover antiquity for a longer form work. Keep writing.

I would have called the keypad display segmented or described it as glowing red rather than digital.
But your choice isn't really incorrect. Travis wouldn't have owned a classic HP and really wouldn't have understood much of the tech of the time. Staff would have been working from the very rare terminals or even rarer custom CRT setups attached to a mainframe. Teletypes would have still been common for anything not running in batch mode.
My only quibble is that the actual computer mainframes would have been separate from the Ops room if they were something like a small IBM System/360 or a rather new S/370. Now if we were talking minis, No IBM kit(as that was highly slanted to businesses with the System/3), maybe an HP2000, a DG Nova, and definitely a smattering of DEC PDP-11 racks. But those would still likely be in another room.
As revolutionary as the HP calculators (including the 9800 line that evolved (kind of...) into the HP9000 line) were, I'm still partial to the PDP-11.

Travis needs to head back and grab an HP-35 if he can find one, and plenty of batteries.

Anonymous Sun 10 Apr 2022 06:24:45 No.46825925 Report
Quoted By: >>46829082 >>46832023
>>46824641
Mainframes and some minis would be in a dedicated room with the geeks. The Ops center would be projection screens with a bunch of terminals.
This was a typical PDP-11/70 (the successor of the PDP-11/45 that was introduced in '72) setup in 1975
Now, the (part of a) FOSDIC system in your pic was essentially a frontend for a UNIVAC or PDP-11, just a massive input device. Except the same applies - keep the non-operators away from all those switches and lights and dials and very expensive parts.

There are some things that Travis would be able to draw on.
If he was piloting in the military, Travis would have had an opportunity to see a FADAC variant, especially if he'd been in Vietnam. As a helicopter pilot, someone he knew would have flown one of them into the jungle. That would have been his concept of a computer besides the classic teletype.
But mostly, someone with his level of training would have walked into such a room and been like
>this resembles my concept of computer in the same way that a fighter jet resembles my chopper
which is pretty close to what you did.

I'm just being a bit particular because that's my favorite era of computers. 16-bit falls aside for 32-bit, big iron mainframes, the beginnings of the microcomputer and then microprocessors moving into the home.

One other thing to keep in mind is that the standard for teletypes at the time of 1972 would be the ASR-33. If you really need a vector graphics terminal, you had a Tektronix 4010 terminal.
And none of these had the familiar numerical keypad we're used to. If you look up that FADAC, it's a good example of something that did have a 10-key numerical.

But you also brought up an interesting point I'd overlooked.
Since you want to keep radio equipment away from computers, the main Ops room would be separated from the radio stuff as well.
Plenty of early home computers had issues with interference, like the PET 2001 and the TRS Model 1. Even later systems weren't perfect.
I'd bet that any facility with high-powered transmitters receivers would be shielded externally and then the equipment rooms as well.
And now I'm wishing I still have the contact info for someone I knew that wintered at the old South Pole facility a few times. The guy was a hoot when it came to computer problem stories, such as the ssh connection with a 3-5 second ping time - on a good day.

Anonymous Sun 10 Apr 2022 16:51:27 No.46834110 Report
Quoted By: >>46834768
>>46833792
Lots of people out there think they have the chops to design a new encryption system from the ground up. In the biz, before you can get people to take you and your new, neva-been-dun-befo algorithm seriously, first you have to make your bones. You make your bones by cracking encryption designed by other people who thought their ideas had never been tried before.

Also, stipulated: one thing about the biz that nobody talks about much is that, yes, there are organized l33t h4x0r groups out there who break other people's shit just on general principles, and yes, there are nation-state threat actors out there who have enormous resources and who may intend espionage, industrial or otherwise... 90%+ of "super duper mysterious unknown super sophisticated hacker attacks" are inside jobs, perpetrated by employees who are disgruntled, or who think they can get rich by selling the company's data.

It turns out that when you outsource your software dev to a Third World country where people live in mud huts and pay your devs two cents a month, that two cents a month doesn't buy loyalty. Anyone who waves a ten dollar bill under their noses will walk away with all your passwords, all your keys, and anything else they can think of to pass along. Who saw that one coming?

Likewise, how good the encryption built into your routers is doesn't matter if some mysterious and secretive group (*cough* NSA *cough*) has induced the manufacturer to ship the hardware to you with a special software package installed that gives them a back door and lets them see all your traffic in the clear, no matter how long the keys are. Tempting as it is to "4096 bit RSA all the things! there is a point of diminishing returns where it starts to have serious effects on network speeds, if misconfigured it has the potential to bring the network down anyway... and more than a few IT departments install the new routers and switches right out of the box with default settings and default passwords.

If you don't know, you get close enough and learn what you really don't know. Then you avoid saying anything that breaks disbelief...unless you have a good alt-history Space Bats idea that lets you drop in whatever you want.

But seriously, look up a lot of the stuff I and others have mentioned. Give yourself an evening and get into that vibe. Play with a virtual PDP-11 front panel.
Travis, or another character, might need to touch the tech at some point. Having a small list of interesting things like the physical dimensions of a removable disk pack or what the real machines sounded like might give you some interesting Chekov's guns

I've been having fun reading, so hopefully the tech talk helps you in return.

Seconding this
It depends on whether you're going first or third person. Each has benefits to expansive worldbuilding, but both require you to know enough yourself before you start writing. Treat your first draft like a mystery. You're discovering all the clues on the setting and what's really important.
You also should have a good idea who your characters are. That will let seemingly unrelated bits gell into a whole down the line
